@GaryMarcus ...to redesign the environments around them.

For decades, digital files would get corrupted or deleted at rates far exceeding loss of paper docs, so we redesigned around 'Save your work, it's your fault if you don't.'

Amazon warehouses have human exclusion zones for same reason

@GaryMarcus 'Safe as humans' makes the bet unwinnable. 

When cars appeared, they weren't safe as carriages. The next step wasn't making cars safer, but excluding everything else-carriages, horses, bikes, pedestrians. Crosswalks and highways are both exclusion zones.

L5 = L3+human exclusion

@bilalfarooqui @Jessicalessin @elonmusk @Twitter I agree that this is not surprising at all. (Contra 
@Jessicalessin, who made up a guy she thought was Elon.) 

The difference is that communities, once broken, can't be unbroken with money.

@DudeOther @benzado That supposes there is a one-dimensional metric of quality. 

If you are choosing a new member of a group, you are always choosing bundles of qualities, and always in comparison to the qualities of the existing group.

There's no linear, value-neutral scale of merit.

@UriBram @florencehinder Linus (who's patched the same codebase for 3 decades) says that to fix a bug, you have to characterize the problem and invent a solution. 

These are often done by different people, and he thinks the first step is the harder one.

Cathedral and the Bazaar, if you want the quote.

